choices.text: the best solution for ending "marital suffering." In many Christian congregations in Equatorial Guinea, women often remain silent, sitting quietly without engaging with the sermon preached by their pastor. Upon marriage, women, especially those from rural areas, are required to leave school. This has an impact on girls and women being able to make and enforce laws and policies. In 2014, it was reported that only six per cent of cabinet ministers are women, only 13 per cent of members of parliament are women and only 18 per cent of civil servants are women. The law in Equatorial Guinea equalizes the liability of spouses to family assets and eliminates the husband's preference for stakes and the wife's obligation to maintain the marital home and family expenses. Also, it grants the right for marital property to be divided equally if the marriage does not produce any child.
